{"title_page": "Perodua Kancil", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image = Perodua Kancil (first generation) (front), Kuala Lumpur.jpg\n| name = Perodua Kancil (L200)\n| manufacturer = [[Perodua]]\n| production = 1994\u20132009<br />722,223 built\n| class = [[Kei car]]<br />[[City car]]\n| platform = \n| related = [[Daihatsu Mira#L200 series (1990)|Daihatsu Mira (L200)]]\n| layout = [[FF layout]]\n| body_style = 5-door [[hatchback]]\n| engine = 659&nbsp;cc ''[[Daihatsu E-series engine#EF-series (660 cc)|Daihatsu EF-CL]]'' [[SOHC]] [[Straight-3|I3]]<br>849&nbsp;cc ''[[Daihatsu E-series engine#ED-series (850 cc)|Daihatsu ED-10]]'' [[SOHC]] [[Straight-3|I3]]<br>849&nbsp;cc ''[[Daihatsu E-series engine#ED-series (850 cc)|Daihatsu ED-DE]]'' [[DOHC]] [[Straight-3|I3]]\n| successor = [[Perodua Viva]]\n| transmission = 4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]<br>5-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]<br>3-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| length = {{convert|3395|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1405|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1415|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2280|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|650|-|690|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n| aka = Perodua Nippa (United Kingdom)<br />Daihatsu Ceria (Indonesia)\n}}\n\nThe '''Perodua Kancil''' (also known as the '''Perodua Nippa''' in the United Kingdom, and '''Daihatsu Ceria''' in Indonesia) is a [[city car]] manufactured by [[Malaysia]]n automobile manufacturer [[Perodua]] from August 1994 to 2009.<ref name=WOC>{{cite book | title = World of Cars 2006\u00b72007 | publisher = Media Connection Sp. z o.o. | location = Warsaw, Poland | page = 203 | year = 2006 }}</ref> The Kancil is a [[rebadging|rebadged]] third generation [[Daihatsu Mira]].\n\n== History ==\n{{Multiple image\n| align = left\n| direction = vertical\n| width = \n| image1 = Perodua Kancil (first generation) (front), Kuala Lumpur.jpg\n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Perodua Kancil rv.jpg\n| caption2 = 1994-1997\n| image3 = Perodua Kancil (first generation, first facelift) (front), Kuala Lumpur.jpg\n| caption3 = \n| image4 = Perodua Kancil (first generation, first facelift) (rear), Kuala Lumpur.jpg\n| caption4 = 1997-2000\n| image5 = Perodua Kancil (first generation, second facelift) (front), Serdang.jpg\n| caption5 = \n| image6 = Perodua Kancil (first generation, second facelift) (rear), Serdang.jpg\n| caption6 = 2000-2002\n| image7 = Perodua Kancil (first generation, third facelift) (front), Seri Kembangan.jpg\n| caption7 = \n| image8 = Perodua Kancil (first generation, third facelift) (rear), Seri Kembangan.jpg\n| caption8 = 2002-2009\n}}The Kancil was Perodua's first car after its founding in 1992.<ref name=\"WOC\" /> It is a small five-door hatchback vehicle on a [[monocoque]] framework that can seat five people. The Kancil, like its predecessors, is a slightly modified [[Daihatsu Mira]] L200; [[rebadging]] is common in Malaysia's automotive industry, having begun in 1985 with first car manufacturer [[Proton (company)|Proton]], which based its cars on retired models of [[Mitsubishi Motors]]. Subsequent Kancils were only rejuvenated cosmetically as Perodua maintained the monocoque structure and tweaked its engines.\n\nThe Kancil is named after the [[Chevrotain|mouse deer]], a native animal was commonly found in Malaysian jungle. The car was available with two engines, a 660&nbsp;cc version with {{convert|31|PS|kW|abbr=on}} and an 850 with {{convert|37|PS|kW|abbr=on}}. Four- or five-speed manual transmissions were available (four-speed was not available in the 850) or a three-speed automatic.<ref name=Kancilguy>{{cite web | title = Kancil Specifications | url = http://lordq8.tripod.com/kancil_specification.htm | work = Mira/Kancil Turbo Site | first = Eddie | last = Hasrine | accessdate = 2013-01-13 }}</ref>\n\nThe Kancil was unveiled on the 29th of August 1994.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paultan.org/2014/09/30/gallery-perodua-kancil-axia-malaysias-cheapest-car/|title=GALLERY: Perodua Kancil to Perodua Axia, Malaysia's most affordable car through the ages|date=2014-09-30|website=Paul Tan's Automotive News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref> At launch two variants were on offered: EX and GX both powered by a 660 cc engine and both paired to a manual transmission. 4-speed manual for the EX and 5-speed manual for the GX.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://autoworld.com.my/news/2009/07/20/Out-goes-the-Kancil-in-comes-ViVA-660BX/|title=Out goes the Kancil, in comes ViVA 660BX|last=Kon|date=2009-07-20|website=Autoworld.com.my|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> \n\nIn January 1995, the Perodua Kancil EZ was launched. It came with an automatic transmission and in addition to the existing equipment on the GX variant, there was colored bumpers, gear lock, side protector molding, hazard sign and the first-aid kit for metallic and mica models only. It was launched at RM28,931.14 for the solid colors (Kristal White and Bunga Raya Red), RM 29,838.14 for the Metallic version (Kilauan Silver) and RM 30,214.00 for the Mica version (Blue Mica) in Peninsular Malaysia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=1995&article=1|title=Perodua.com :: News & Events :: 1995|date=2004-06-11|access-date=2017-09-03|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040611145814/http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=1995&article=1|archivedate=2004-06-11}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1996, the Perodua Kancil 850cc version was launched. It came with both GX (manual transmission) and EZ (automatic transmission) variants in addition to the existing 660cc version. Their features and colours are carried over from both GX and EZ of 660cc version, with additional of front power windows, and with Violet Purple colour instead of Blue Mica and Classic Blue. Their prices were quite little higher than 660cc versions because of the bigger 850cc engine volume and power, as well as the latter additional equipment. Besides both variants, the additional 850cc GX based Kancil Era variant was also introduced.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOn 27 August 1997, the Perodua Kancil was facelifted. Changes included new design for the larger front grille, rear garnish, rounded indicator lights, clear rear signal lenses (amber in pre-facelift) and different wheel caps designs, new cabin upholstery with the use of improved seat fabric and 2 front washer nozzles. The Kancil 850 cc series, got new white faced metres and adjustable head rest. Prices were between RM 24,833.74 to RM 33,465.84.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=1997&article=3|title=Perodua.com :: News & Events :: 1997|date=2003-12-26|access-date=2017-09-03|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031226220523/http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=1997&article=3|archivedate=2003-12-26}}</ref>  \n\nOn 3 May 1998, the Perodua Kancil EX extra was launched. It came with a 660cc engine and 5-speed manual transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=1998&article=1|title=Perodua.com.my :: News & Events :: 1998|date=2004-02-20|access-date=2017-09-03|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040220152432/http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=1998&article=1|archivedate=2004-02-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, the car was given another slight facelift consisting of body-coloured side mouldings, a new grille and reprofiled front bumper with larger indicators, and electrical adjustable side mirrors were equipped for 850cc models.This facelift was available with three variants: 660 EX, 850 EX and 850 EZ.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001019080332/http://www.perodua.com.my:80/kancil/index.htm|title=Wayback Machine|date=2000-10-19|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>\n\nThe Kancil received a more extensive restyling in September 2002,<ref name=\"WOC\" /> featuring rounder headlights, taillights and bumpers; its rear license plate was also repositioned onto its [[Trunk (automobile)#Door|hatch]] from the bumper below. Its interior features a flushed dashboard with the combination instrumentation panel placed in the middle similar to that of the [[Toyota Yaris]]. However, it is still mechanically identical to its predecessor, except for the EZi automatic transmission variant which was given a fuel-injected powerplant though this variant wasn't available at launch. Perodua cited Daihatsu\u2019s thorough testing procedures and the engine being made locally with many local component for the EZi variant to be only introduced later on. At launch only manual transmission equipped variants were available: 660EX and 850EX.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://autoworld.com.my/news/2002/09/28/The-New-Perodua-Kancil-UPDATED-STORY/|title=The New Perodua Kancil \u2013 UPDATED STORY - Autoworld.com.my|last=3348|date=2002-09-28|work=Autoworld.com.my|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nIn February 2003, the Perodua Kancil EZi was launched. It came with an automatic transmission and an electronic fuel injected engine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=2003&article=11|title=Perodua.com.my :: News & Events :: 2003|date=2004-02-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040220052557/http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=2003&article=11|archivedate=2004-02-20|url-status=bot: unknown|access-date=2017-09-03}}</ref>\n\nBetween June<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040610130009/http://www.perodua.com.my:80/our_cars.php?sub_page=kancil&sub_nav=price|title=Perodua.com :: Our Cars :: kancil :: price|date=2004-06-10|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref> and August 2004<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040804070919/http://www.perodua.com.my:80/our_cars.php?sub_page=kancil&sub_nav=price|title=Perodua.com :: Our Cars :: kancil :: price|date=2004-08-04|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>, a 660 EXb variant or 660 EX Basic variant was made available as the new base model. Notable omissions from the 660 EX variant included the passenger visor, a clock, door visors, rear wiper, a radio with speakers and an alarm with central locking. Solid Ivory White was the only colour option for this variant.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217131934/http://www.perodua.com.my/download/brochure/kancil_brochure.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=2007-12-17|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>\n\nBetween May<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217131934/http://www.perodua.com.my/download/brochure/kancil_brochure.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=2007-12-17|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref> and December 2005<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060217174137/http://www.perodua.com.my/our_cars.php?sub_page=kancil&sub_nav=price&car_model=850exs|title=Perodua.com :: Our Cars :: kancil :: price|date=2006-02-17|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>, a 850 EXS variant was made available. This variant stood for special edition and was priced not much different to the 850 EX variant which it shared the same powertrain (engine and transmission combination) with. Key features of this variant included 12\" alloy wheels like on the 850 EZi variant, a CD player. skirting/bodykit, blue graphics for the instrument cluster, sliver painted centre cluster and a leather wrapped steering wheel. Metallic Ebony Black and Metallic Glittering Sliver were the only two colour options for this variant. It is interesting to note that other variants either had no radio or a radio with cassette making this variant the only Kancil variant to come with a CD player. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFrom July 2005 a tuned Kancil SE version was also available.<ref name=\"WOC3\">{{cite book|title=World of Cars 2006\u00b72007|publisher=Media Connection Sp. z o.o.|year=2006|location=Warsaw, Poland|page=203}}</ref>\n\nBetween February<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080216031632/http://www.perodua.com.my:80/index.php?section=ourcars&page=kancil&action=price|title=Perodua : Kancil Price|date=2008-02-16|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref> and March 2008<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080301172608/http://www.perodua.com.my:80/index.php?section=ourcars&page=kancil&action=price|title=Perodua : Kancil Price|date=2008-03-01|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>, both the 850 EXS and 850 EZi model was dropped.\n\nProduction of Kancil ceased on 20 July 2009 and replaced by the basic model of [[Perodua Viva]] known as Perodua Viva 660BX which comes in manual transmission only.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://paultan.org/2009/07/20/perodua-viva-660-bx-replaces-the-kancil/|title=Perodua Viva 660 BX replaces the Kancil|date=2009-07-20|work=Paul Tan's Automotive News|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Powertrains  ==\nThe Kancil was sold with various engines and transmissions:\n* 659 cc Daihatsu EF-CL single over head cam, three-cylinder carbureted [[Straight engine|in-line engine]] producing {{Convert|31|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}}. Paired to a four speed manual transmission or a five-speed [[manual transmission]] or a three-speed automatic. Application - 660 EX, 660 EXb, 660 EX Extra, 660 GX and 660 EZ variants. \n* 847 cc Daihatsu ED-10 three-cylinder carbureted [[Straight engine|in-line engine]] producing {{Convert|37|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}}. Paired to a five-speed [[manual transmission]] or a three-speed [[automatic transmission]]. Applications - 850 EX, 850 GX. 850 EZ and 850 EXS variants.\n* 847 cc Daihatsu ED-DE three-cylinder fuel-injected [[Straight engine|in-line engine]], {{Convert|49|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}. Paired to a three-speed [[automatic transmission]] only. Application - 850 EZi variant only.\n\n== Sales ==\nFollowing its release in 1994, the Kancil became an instant success in Malaysia. The Kancil is popular with beginner drivers and is commonly used in Malaysian driving schools. It was also preferable for its fuel efficiency and ease of parking due to its size. In December 1995, Perodua produced its 50,000th Kancil. By January 1997, 100,000 Kancils had been manufactured, and by 1999 250,000 had been built. Average monthly production during its fifteen years was 4,000, with October 2002 being the most successful month with 7,700 built.<ref name=\"MYstar2\">{{cite journal|last=Mahalingam|first=Eugene|date=2009-07-21|title=Perodua on track to achieve 2009 sales target|url=http://biz.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2009/7/21/business/4356498&sec=business|journal=The Star|location=Malaysia|publisher=Star Publications (M) Bhd|accessdate=2013-01-13}}</ref> In total 722,223 Kancils were built, of which around 14,000 were exported.<ref name=\"MYstar2\" />\n\n== Export ==\nThe Kancil was exported to a total of 19 different countries.<ref name=\":1\" /> This includes Brunei and Mauritius starting from 1996<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paultan.org/2016/04/07/perodua-exports-310-units-of-myvi-alza-1-5-se-to-brunei/|title=Perodua exports 310 units of Myvi, Alza 1.5 to Brunei|date=2016-04-07|website=Paul Tan's Automotive News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sinarharian.com.my/article/44067/SISIPAN/Turbo/Perodua-tembus-pasaran-Mauritius|title=Perodua tembus pasaran Mauritius|date=2019-08-21|website=Sinarharian|language=ms|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> and Sri Lanka from 1997<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/business/2017/06/246612/perodua-launches-bezza-sri-lanka|website=www.nst.com.my|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>.\n\n=== {{anchor|Nippa}} United Kingdom ===\nThe Perodua Kancil was sold in the [[United Kingdom]] as the '''Perodua Nippa''' in September 1997. It was priced at just over \u00a35,000 (cut to \u00a34,999 in 1999) it was the cheapest new car on sale there until it was replaced by the [[Perodua Kelisa]] four years later.<ref>{{cite web | author = Enright, Andy | title = Perodua Nippa (1997-2001): Malaysian Invasion | url = http://uk.cars.yahoo.com/car-reviews/car-and-driving/perodua-nippa-2004307.html | date = 2004-08-04 | work = Yahoo! Cars | publisher = Yahoo! Inc }}</ref> The Nippa was exclusively sold with 850cc fuel injected engines, engine code unknown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020710200657/http://www.perodua-uk.com:80/nippaspec.htm|title=Perodua UK Nippa Specifications|date=2002-07-10|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"120\">\nFile:2001 Perodua Nippa EX 850cc Front.jpg|Perodua Nippa\n</gallery>\n\n=== {{anchor|Ceria}} Indonesia ===\nIn Indonesia, the Perodua Kancil was sold as the '''Daihatsu Ceria'''. The Ceria, meaning \"happy\" or \"cheerful\" in Malay/Indonesian, was introduced at the 11th Gaikindo Auto Expo in Jakarta in July 2001.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Harsanto|first=Damar|date=2001-07-21|title=Auto expo goes ahead despite political showdown|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2001/07/21/auto-expo-goes-ahead-despite-political-showdown.html|journal=Jakarta Post|location=Jakarta, Indonesia|publisher=PT. Bina Media Tenggara|page=3|accessdate=2013-01-13|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305000958/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2001/07/21/auto-expo-goes-ahead-despite-political-showdown.html|archivedate=2016-03-05}}</ref> It had been preceded the year before by the Daihatsu KX-P \"concept car\" - a standard Kancil equipped with a leather and wood interior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daihatsu.com/brand/motorshow/indonesia00/kx-p/kx-p_e.pdf|title=Press Information: KX-P|year=2000|publisher=Astra Daihatsu Motor|accessdate=2013-01-13|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091014165029/http://www.daihatsu.com/brand/motorshow/indonesia00/kx-p/kx-p_e.pdf|archivedate=2009-10-14}}</ref> The Ceria was only available with the larger 850&nbsp;cc engine with a carburettor and {{convert|37|PS|kW|abbr=on}}, in two equipment levels: the base model KL and the more extra-spec KX, which received a chromed grille.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daihatsu.com/brand/motorshow/indonesia01/ceria/ceria_e.pdf|title=Press Information: Ceria|year=2001|publisher=Astra Daihatsu Motor|page=3|accessdate=2013-01-13|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728051945/http://www.daihatsu.com/brand/motorshow/indonesia01/ceria/ceria_e.pdf|archivedate=2010-07-28}}</ref> It was discontinued in 2006. It was later superseded in 2012 by a spiritual successor, the [[Daihatsu Ayla|Ayla]].\n\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"120\">\nFile:Daihatsu Ceria (front).jpg|2001\u20132003 Daihatsu Ceria\nFile:2003 Daihatsu Ceria KX hatchback (L201; 01-09-2019), South Tangerang.jpg|2003\u20132006 Daihatsu Ceria\n</gallery>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Perodua Kancil}}\n{{commons category|Daihatsu Ceria}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110723193826/http://www.perodua.co.uk/kancil.htm Perodua UK]\n* [http://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=6710 Kancil specifications]\n\n{{Perodua}}\n{{Perodua vehicles}}\n{{Daihatsu timeline}}\n\n[[Category:Perodua vehicles|Kancil]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1994]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image = Perodua Kancil (first generation) (front), Kuala Lumpur.jpg\n| name = Perodua Kancil (L200)\n| manufacturer = [[Perodua]]\n| production = 1994\u20132009<br />722,223 built\n| class = [[Kei car]]<br />[[City car]]\n| platform = \n| related = [[Daihatsu Mira#L200 series (1990)|Daihatsu Mira (L200)]]\n| layout = [[FF layout]]\n| body_style = 5-door [[hatchback]]\n| engine = 659&nbsp;cc ''[[Daihatsu E-series engine#EF-series (660 cc)|Daihatsu EF-CL]]'' [[SOHC]] [[Straight-3|I3]]<br>849&nbsp;cc ''[[Daihatsu E-series engine#ED-series (850 cc)|Daihatsu ED-10]]'' [[SOHC]] [[Straight-3|I3]]<br>849&nbsp;cc ''[[Daihatsu E-series engine#ED-series (850 cc)|Daihatsu ED-DE]]'' [[DOHC]] [[Straight-3|I3]]\n| successor = [[Perodua Viva]]\n| transmission = 4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]<br>5-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]<br>3-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| length = {{convert|3395|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1405|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1415|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2280|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|650|-|690|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n| aka = Perodua Nippa (United Kingdom)<br />Daihatsu Ceria (Indonesia)\n}}\n\nThe '''Perodua Kancil''' (also known as the '''Perodua Nippa''' in the United Kingdom, and '''Daihatsu Ceria''' in Indonesia) is a [[city car]] manufactured by [[Malaysia]]n automobile manufacturer [[Perodua]] from August 1994 to 2009.<ref name=WOC>{{cite book | title = World of Cars 2006\u00b72007 | publisher = Media Connection Sp. z o.o. | location = Warsaw, Poland | page = 203 | year = 2006 }}</ref> The Kancil is a [[rebadging|rebadged]] third generation [[Daihatsu Mira]].\n\n== History ==\n{{Multiple image\n| align = left\n| direction = vertical\n| width = \n| image1 = Perodua Kancil (first generation) (front), Kuala Lumpur.jpg\n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Perodua Kancil rv.jpg\n| caption2 = 1994-1997\n| image3 = Perodua Kancil (first generation, first facelift) (front), Kuala Lumpur.jpg\n| caption3 = \n| image4 = Perodua Kancil (first generation, first facelift) (rear), Kuala Lumpur.jpg\n| caption4 = 1997-2000\n| image5 = Perodua Kancil (first generation, second facelift) (front), Serdang.jpg\n| caption5 = \n| image6 = Perodua Kancil (first generation, second facelift) (rear), Serdang.jpg\n| caption6 = 2000-2002\n| image7 = Perodua Kancil (first generation, third facelift) (front), Seri Kembangan.jpg\n| caption7 = \n| image8 = Perodua Kancil (first generation, third facelift) (rear), Seri Kembangan.jpg\n| caption8 = 2002-2009\n}}The Kancil was Perodua's first car after its founding in 1992.<ref name=\"WOC\" /> It is a small five-door hatchback vehicle on a [[monocoque]] framework that can seat five people. The Kancil, like its predecessors, is a slightly modified [[Daihatsu Mira]] L200; [[rebadging]] is common in Malaysia's automotive industry, having begun in 1985 with first car manufacturer [[Proton (company)|Proton]], which based its cars on retired models of [[Mitsubishi Motors]]. Subsequent Kancils were only rejuvenated cosmetically as Perodua maintained the monocoque structure and tweaked its engines.\n\nThe Kancil is named after the [[Lesser mouse dear|mouse deer]], a native animal was commonly found in Malaysian jungle. The car was available with two engines, a 660&nbsp;cc version with {{convert|31|PS|kW|abbr=on}} and an 850 with {{convert|37|PS|kW|abbr=on}}. Four- or five-speed manual transmissions were available (four-speed was not available in the 850) or a three-speed automatic.<ref name=Kancilguy>{{cite web | title = Kancil Specifications | url = http://lordq8.tripod.com/kancil_specification.htm | work = Mira/Kancil Turbo Site | first = Eddie | last = Hasrine | accessdate = 2013-01-13 }}</ref>\n\nThe Kancil was unveiled on the 29th of August 1994.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paultan.org/2014/09/30/gallery-perodua-kancil-axia-malaysias-cheapest-car/|title=GALLERY: Perodua Kancil to Perodua Axia, Malaysia's most affordable car through the ages|date=2014-09-30|website=Paul Tan's Automotive News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref> At launch two variants were on offered: EX and GX both powered by a 660 cc engine and both paired to a manual transmission. 4-speed manual for the EX and 5-speed manual for the GX.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://autoworld.com.my/news/2009/07/20/Out-goes-the-Kancil-in-comes-ViVA-660BX/|title=Out goes the Kancil, in comes ViVA 660BX|last=Kon|date=2009-07-20|website=Autoworld.com.my|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> \n\nIn January 1995, the Perodua Kancil EZ was launched. It came with an automatic transmission and in addition to the existing equipment on the GX variant, there was colored bumpers, gear lock, side protector molding, hazard sign and the first-aid kit for metallic and mica models only. It was launched at RM28,931.14 for the solid colors (Kristal White and Bunga Raya Red), RM 29,838.14 for the Metallic version (Kilauan Silver) and RM 30,214.00 for the Mica version (Blue Mica) in Peninsular Malaysia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=1995&article=1|title=Perodua.com :: News & Events :: 1995|date=2004-06-11|access-date=2017-09-03|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040611145814/http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=1995&article=1|archivedate=2004-06-11}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1996, the Perodua Kancil 850cc version was launched. It came with both GX (manual transmission) and EZ (automatic transmission) variants in addition to the existing 660cc version. Their features and colours are carried over from both GX and EZ of 660cc version, with additional of front power windows, and with Violet Purple colour instead of Blue Mica and Classic Blue. Their prices were quite little higher than 660cc versions because of the bigger 850cc engine volume and power, as well as the latter additional equipment. Besides both variants, the additional 850cc GX based Kancil Era variant was also introduced.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOn 27 August 1997, the Perodua Kancil was facelifted. Changes included new design for the larger front grille, rear garnish, rounded indicator lights, clear rear signal lenses (amber in pre-facelift) and different wheel caps designs, new cabin upholstery with the use of improved seat fabric and 2 front washer nozzles. The Kancil 850 cc series, got new white faced metres and adjustable head rest. Prices were between RM 24,833.74 to RM 33,465.84.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=1997&article=3|title=Perodua.com :: News & Events :: 1997|date=2003-12-26|access-date=2017-09-03|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031226220523/http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=1997&article=3|archivedate=2003-12-26}}</ref>  \n\nOn 3 May 1998, the Perodua Kancil EX extra was launched. It came with a 660cc engine and 5-speed manual transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=1998&article=1|title=Perodua.com.my :: News & Events :: 1998|date=2004-02-20|access-date=2017-09-03|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040220152432/http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=1998&article=1|archivedate=2004-02-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, the car was given another slight facelift consisting of body-coloured side mouldings, a new grille and reprofiled front bumper with larger indicators, and electrical adjustable side mirrors were equipped for 850cc models.This facelift was available with three variants: 660 EX, 850 EX and 850 EZ.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001019080332/http://www.perodua.com.my:80/kancil/index.htm|title=Wayback Machine|date=2000-10-19|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>\n\nThe Kancil received a more extensive restyling in September 2002,<ref name=\"WOC\" /> featuring rounder headlights, taillights and bumpers; its rear license plate was also repositioned onto its [[Trunk (automobile)#Door|hatch]] from the bumper below. Its interior features a flushed dashboard with the combination instrumentation panel placed in the middle similar to that of the [[Toyota Yaris]]. However, it is still mechanically identical to its predecessor, except for the EZi automatic transmission variant which was given a fuel-injected powerplant though this variant wasn't available at launch. Perodua cited Daihatsu\u2019s thorough testing procedures and the engine being made locally with many local component for the EZi variant to be only introduced later on. At launch only manual transmission equipped variants were available: 660EX and 850EX.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://autoworld.com.my/news/2002/09/28/The-New-Perodua-Kancil-UPDATED-STORY/|title=The New Perodua Kancil \u2013 UPDATED STORY - Autoworld.com.my|last=3348|date=2002-09-28|work=Autoworld.com.my|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nIn February 2003, the Perodua Kancil EZi was launched. It came with an automatic transmission and an electronic fuel injected engine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=2003&article=11|title=Perodua.com.my :: News & Events :: 2003|date=2004-02-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040220052557/http://www.perodua.com.my/news_events.php?sub_page=2003&article=11|archivedate=2004-02-20|url-status=bot: unknown|access-date=2017-09-03}}</ref>\n\nBetween June<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040610130009/http://www.perodua.com.my:80/our_cars.php?sub_page=kancil&sub_nav=price|title=Perodua.com :: Our Cars :: kancil :: price|date=2004-06-10|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref> and August 2004<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040804070919/http://www.perodua.com.my:80/our_cars.php?sub_page=kancil&sub_nav=price|title=Perodua.com :: Our Cars :: kancil :: price|date=2004-08-04|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>, a 660 EXb variant or 660 EX Basic variant was made available as the new base model. Notable omissions from the 660 EX variant included the passenger visor, a clock, door visors, rear wiper, a radio with speakers and an alarm with central locking. Solid Ivory White was the only colour option for this variant.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217131934/http://www.perodua.com.my/download/brochure/kancil_brochure.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=2007-12-17|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>\n\nBetween May<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217131934/http://www.perodua.com.my/download/brochure/kancil_brochure.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=2007-12-17|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref> and December 2005<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060217174137/http://www.perodua.com.my/our_cars.php?sub_page=kancil&sub_nav=price&car_model=850exs|title=Perodua.com :: Our Cars :: kancil :: price|date=2006-02-17|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>, a 850 EXS variant was made available. This variant stood for special edition and was priced not much different to the 850 EX variant which it shared the same powertrain (engine and transmission combination) with. Key features of this variant included 12\" alloy wheels like on the 850 EZi variant, a CD player. skirting/bodykit, blue graphics for the instrument cluster, sliver painted centre cluster and a leather wrapped steering wheel. Metallic Ebony Black and Metallic Glittering Sliver were the only two colour options for this variant. It is interesting to note that other variants either had no radio or a radio with cassette making this variant the only Kancil variant to come with a CD player. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFrom July 2005 a tuned Kancil SE version was also available.<ref name=\"WOC3\">{{cite book|title=World of Cars 2006\u00b72007|publisher=Media Connection Sp. z o.o.|year=2006|location=Warsaw, Poland|page=203}}</ref>\n\nBetween February<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080216031632/http://www.perodua.com.my:80/index.php?section=ourcars&page=kancil&action=price|title=Perodua : Kancil Price|date=2008-02-16|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref> and March 2008<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080301172608/http://www.perodua.com.my:80/index.php?section=ourcars&page=kancil&action=price|title=Perodua : Kancil Price|date=2008-03-01|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>, both the 850 EXS and 850 EZi model was dropped.\n\nProduction of Kancil ceased on 20 July 2009 and replaced by the basic model of [[Perodua Viva]] known as Perodua Viva 660BX which comes in manual transmission only.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://paultan.org/2009/07/20/perodua-viva-660-bx-replaces-the-kancil/|title=Perodua Viva 660 BX replaces the Kancil|date=2009-07-20|work=Paul Tan's Automotive News|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Powertrains  ==\nThe Kancil was sold with various engines and transmissions:\n* 659 cc Daihatsu EF-CL single over head cam, three-cylinder carbureted [[Straight engine|in-line engine]] producing {{Convert|31|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}}. Paired to a four speed manual transmission or a five-speed [[manual transmission]] or a three-speed automatic. Application - 660 EX, 660 EXb, 660 EX Extra, 660 GX and 660 EZ variants. \n* 847 cc Daihatsu ED-10 three-cylinder carbureted [[Straight engine|in-line engine]] producing {{Convert|37|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}}. Paired to a five-speed [[manual transmission]] or a three-speed [[automatic transmission]]. Applications - 850 EX, 850 GX. 850 EZ and 850 EXS variants.\n* 847 cc Daihatsu ED-DE three-cylinder fuel-injected [[Straight engine|in-line engine]], {{Convert|49|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}. Paired to a three-speed [[automatic transmission]] only. Application - 850 EZi variant only.\n\n== Sales ==\nFollowing its release in 1994, the Kancil became an instant success in Malaysia. The Kancil is popular with beginner drivers and is commonly used in Malaysian driving schools. It was also preferable for its fuel efficiency and ease of parking due to its size. In December 1995, Perodua produced its 50,000th Kancil. By January 1997, 100,000 Kancils had been manufactured, and by 1999 250,000 had been built. Average monthly production during its fifteen years was 4,000, with October 2002 being the most successful month with 7,700 built.<ref name=\"MYstar2\">{{cite journal|last=Mahalingam|first=Eugene|date=2009-07-21|title=Perodua on track to achieve 2009 sales target|url=http://biz.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2009/7/21/business/4356498&sec=business|journal=The Star|location=Malaysia|publisher=Star Publications (M) Bhd|accessdate=2013-01-13}}</ref> In total 722,223 Kancils were built, of which around 14,000 were exported.<ref name=\"MYstar2\" />\n\n== Export ==\nThe Kancil was exported to a total of 19 different countries.<ref name=\":1\" /> This includes Brunei and Mauritius starting from 1996<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paultan.org/2016/04/07/perodua-exports-310-units-of-myvi-alza-1-5-se-to-brunei/|title=Perodua exports 310 units of Myvi, Alza 1.5 to Brunei|date=2016-04-07|website=Paul Tan's Automotive News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sinarharian.com.my/article/44067/SISIPAN/Turbo/Perodua-tembus-pasaran-Mauritius|title=Perodua tembus pasaran Mauritius|date=2019-08-21|website=Sinarharian|language=ms|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> and Sri Lanka from 1997<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/business/2017/06/246612/perodua-launches-bezza-sri-lanka|website=www.nst.com.my|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>.\n\n=== {{anchor|Nippa}} United Kingdom ===\nThe Perodua Kancil was sold in the [[United Kingdom]] as the '''Perodua Nippa''' in September 1997. It was priced at just over \u00a35,000 (cut to \u00a34,999 in 1999) it was the cheapest new car on sale there until it was replaced by the [[Perodua Kelisa]] four years later.<ref>{{cite web | author = Enright, Andy | title = Perodua Nippa (1997-2001): Malaysian Invasion | url = http://uk.cars.yahoo.com/car-reviews/car-and-driving/perodua-nippa-2004307.html | date = 2004-08-04 | work = Yahoo! Cars | publisher = Yahoo! Inc }}</ref> The Nippa was exclusively sold with 850cc fuel injected engines, engine code unknown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020710200657/http://www.perodua-uk.com:80/nippaspec.htm|title=Perodua UK Nippa Specifications|date=2002-07-10|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"120\">\nFile:2001 Perodua Nippa EX 850cc Front.jpg|Perodua Nippa\n</gallery>\n\n=== {{anchor|Ceria}} Indonesia ===\nIn Indonesia, the Perodua Kancil was sold as the '''Daihatsu Ceria'''. The Ceria, meaning \"happy\" or \"cheerful\" in Malay/Indonesian, was introduced at the 11th Gaikindo Auto Expo in Jakarta in July 2001.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Harsanto|first=Damar|date=2001-07-21|title=Auto expo goes ahead despite political showdown|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2001/07/21/auto-expo-goes-ahead-despite-political-showdown.html|journal=Jakarta Post|location=Jakarta, Indonesia|publisher=PT. Bina Media Tenggara|page=3|accessdate=2013-01-13|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305000958/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2001/07/21/auto-expo-goes-ahead-despite-political-showdown.html|archivedate=2016-03-05}}</ref> It had been preceded the year before by the Daihatsu KX-P \"concept car\" - a standard Kancil equipped with a leather and wood interior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daihatsu.com/brand/motorshow/indonesia00/kx-p/kx-p_e.pdf|title=Press Information: KX-P|year=2000|publisher=Astra Daihatsu Motor|accessdate=2013-01-13|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091014165029/http://www.daihatsu.com/brand/motorshow/indonesia00/kx-p/kx-p_e.pdf|archivedate=2009-10-14}}</ref> The Ceria was only available with the larger 850&nbsp;cc engine with a carburettor and {{convert|37|PS|kW|abbr=on}}, in two equipment levels: the base model KL and the more extra-spec KX, which received a chromed grille.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daihatsu.com/brand/motorshow/indonesia01/ceria/ceria_e.pdf|title=Press Information: Ceria|year=2001|publisher=Astra Daihatsu Motor|page=3|accessdate=2013-01-13|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728051945/http://www.daihatsu.com/brand/motorshow/indonesia01/ceria/ceria_e.pdf|archivedate=2010-07-28}}</ref> It was discontinued in 2006. It was later superseded in 2012 by a spiritual successor, the [[Daihatsu Ayla|Ayla]].\n\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"120\">\nFile:Daihatsu Ceria (front).jpg|2001\u20132003 Daihatsu Ceria\nFile:2003 Daihatsu Ceria KX hatchback (L201; 01-09-2019), South Tangerang.jpg|2003\u20132006 Daihatsu Ceria\n</gallery>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Perodua Kancil}}\n{{commons category|Daihatsu Ceria}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110723193826/http://www.perodua.co.uk/kancil.htm Perodua UK]\n* [http://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=6710 Kancil specifications]\n\n{{Perodua}}\n{{Perodua vehicles}}\n{{Daihatsu timeline}}\n\n[[Category:Perodua vehicles|Kancil]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1994]]\n", "name_user": "Emelano", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Fixed a broken/dead wikilink.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perodua_Kancil"}
{"title_page": "Hope 103.2", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2009}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| image =\n| format = [[Easy Listening]]\n| owner = [[Hope Media Ltd]], formerly Christian Broadcasting Association\n| name = Hope 103.2\n| airdate = \n| frequency = \n| area = [[Sydney]]\n| slogan = ''There's Always Hope''\n| sister_stations = [[Inspire Digital]]\n| callsign_meaning = '''2''' = [[New South Wales]]\n'''C'''hristian '''B'''roadcasting '''A'''ssociation\n| erp = 50,000 [[watt]]s\n| haat = 204 m<ref>[[height above average terrain|HAAT]] estimated from http://www.itu.int/SRTM3/ using EHAAT.</ref>\n| coordinates = \n| website = [http://www.hope1032.com.au/ http://hope1032.com.au]|\n| city = \n}}\n\n'''Hope 103.2''' is an [[Easy Listening]] station in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]], transmitting on the FM dial at 103.2&nbsp;MHz. Founded as '''2CBA''' by the '''Rev. Vernon Turner''', it commenced [[broadcasting]] on 5 March 1979 and cemented itself as Australia's first Christian [[FM broadcasting|FM]] [[radio station]]. Its mission is 'Communicating Hope to transform life, faith and culture'.\n\nThe station provides a mixed format of [[Christianity|Christian]], [[easy listening]] and hot [[adult contemporary]] music. Its programming includes talk show, Open House, which explores life, faith and hope from a Christian perspective.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://openhousecommunity.com.au/about-open-house.html |title=About The Open House Show |accessdate=11 October 2011}}</ref> Station programming also features competitions, listener interaction, morning devotionals, short Christian spots, as well as broadcasts of church services each Sunday from St. Thomas' North Sydney and St. John's in Parramatta.\n\nSister station [[Inspire Digital]] was the first Australian Community Radio station launched on DAB+ in 2010.\n\nThe radio station relocated from [[Five Dock]] to its current studios in [[Seven Hills, New South Wales|Seven Hills]] (the former home of [[2WS|WSFM]]) and was renamed ''FM103.2'' in 2002, with the tag-line ''The Heart of Sydney''. The station was renamed Heart 103.2 in December 2007, but this was challenged legally by Macquarie Regional Radioworks who held a generic right to the name Heart. It was decided to use \"Sydney's 1032\" as the interim on-air identifier for 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hope1032.com.au/about-us/brief-history/ |title=Hope 103.2's story |accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn Monday, 15 December 2008 at Midnight the station was renamed as Hope 103.2. Listeners offered their suggestions for a new name for the station and Hope was judged the best and most popular.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hope1032.com.au/about-us/brief-history/ |title=Hope 103.2's story |accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nHope FM began broadcasting initially as 2CBA FM 103.2, \"all beautiful music\" in 1979, whose format was continuous easy listening music, mixed with Christian news and messages.  During this period, much of the music played included James Last, Eric Jupp, Richard Clayderman, Klaus Wunderlich,Gunter Noris, Ambros Seelos, Kai Warner (James Last brother),Raymond Lefreve and other similar sounding artists.  Many of these tracks were not always, but often instrumental versions of more popular hits of the 50s 60s 70s, and 80s.  The station ceased this style of programming during late 1999 in favour of the current format.\n\n==Programming==\nThe format of Hope 103.2 is described as \"Contemporary Christian Radio\", which is Christian-infused mainstream light contemporary radio. The program format is designed to reach out to the wider community as well as the Christian community. This is achieved with \"family friendly\" and accessible music with a positive or relational message, whether performed by Christian or non-Christian artists and regardless of whether or not the music is intentionally carrying a Christian message. Hope 103.2 also broadcasts FRESH with David Esquen on Saturday nights, alongside overnight music, other helpful programs such as Time with God with John North, Focus on the Family and more.\n\n===Open House===\nNow on hiatus Open House was on-air from 7 to 10 Sunday evenings, and is a live talk show exploring life, faith and culture from a Christian perspective. From April 2006 to March 2011, the show was hosted by [[Sheridan Voysey]]. From April 2011 until December 2013, Open House was hosted by TV and Radio Broadcaster [[Leigh Hatcher]]. The 2014 host of Open House was [[Dwyane Jeffries]].  The most recent host was [[Stephen O'Doherty]].\n\n===Christmas Hope===\nChristmas Hope is an online music channel and website produced by Hope Media Ltd. The station runs online from November through to January.\n\n===Digital Radio===\n\n==== Inspire Digital ====\nIn November 2010, Hope Media commenced broadcasting of Inspire Digital on [[Digital radio in Australia|Sydney DAB+ Radio]]. It is also available online via live stream on their website. Inspire Digital is Australia's first Christian Digital Radio Station, providing Christian Music and teaching.\n\n==== FRESH Radio ====\nHope Media additionally broadcasts FRESH Radio on their website. While using the FRESH branding, FRESH Radio airs only music.\n\n===Nine News===\nDiscontinued. Prior to the [[Nine Radio]] rebrand from Macquarie Radio Network in 2020, Hope 103.2 broadcast the live simulcasts of Sydney's leading news service, ''[[Nine News]]'' (via [[TCN|Channel Nine Sydney]]), airing every night except Saturdays, at 6:00&nbsp;pm. This commenced in July 2008.\n\nPrior to the Nine Network-Macquarie Radio Group merger, Nine News / 9news.com.au were also the proud sponsors of \u2018'Hope 1032 News'\u2019.\n\n===Album Playlist===\nHope 103.2 plays hits from Christian artists such as [[Francesca Battistelli]], [[Casting Crowns]], [[Third Day]], [[tobyMac]], [[MercyMe]], [[Revive (band)|Revive]] & [[Charmaine (musician)]]. In addition, Hope plays a wide range of contemporary mainstream music.\n\n==Management==\nPhillip Randall, previously CEO of Sonshine FM, Perth, is the CEO of Hope Media Ltd. <br> Dwayne Jeffries is General Manager <br> Ramona Ishac is Group Sales Manager <br> Justin Kendall is Community Relations Manager <br> Lynelle Micati is Finance Manager <br> Stephen Wilkinson is Technical Operations Manager\n\n==2CBA and other Christian radio==\n2CBA is one of Australia's longest established FM radio services, and the longest established full-time Christian radio service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.acma.gov.au/Industry/Broadcast/Community-radio-and-TV |title=ACMA Community Licence allocations and renewals |accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Dan Widdowson]], breakfast presenter\n*[[List of radio stations in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.hope1032.com.au/ Hope 103.2 Website]\n* [http://www.inspiredigitalradio.com/ Inspire Digital]\n* [http://www.hopemedia.com.au/ Hope Media]\n* [http://www.openhousecommunity.com.au/ Open House Website]\n* [http://www.christmashope.com.au/ Christmas Hope Website] *November to January\n* [http://www.hope1032.com.au/ListenLive.asp Fresh Radio - Online Stream]\n\n{{Sydney Radio}}\n{{Christianity in Australia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2cba}}\n[[Category:Christian radio stations in Australia|Hope 103.2]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Sydney|Hope 103.2]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1979|Hope 103.2]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2009}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| image =\n| format = [[Easy Listening]]\n| owner = [[Hope Media Ltd]], formerly Christian Broadcasting Association\n| name = Hope 103.2\n| airdate = \n| frequency = \n| area = [[Sydney]]\n| slogan = ''There's Always Hope''\n| sister_stations = [[Inspire Digital]]\n| callsign_meaning = '''2''' = [[New South Wales]]\n'''C'''hristian '''B'''roadcasting '''A'''ssociation\n| erp = 50,000 [[watt]]s\n| h